Hi Chief Delpinians!

First posting here, on behalf of team 9255. We are a relatively new team, and this year using a swerve drive chassis. We have successfully built/deployed basic CTRE swerve drive code to the robot (RoboRio 2), but are having issues with the motor movement. Moving forward/backward or strafing (basically, anything involving the left controller joystick) momentarily moves the robot in that direction; then, the robot crashes. We have not yet diagnosed software vs hardware issue. Strangely, rotation CW & CCW is very smooth with no issues.

Robot will move forward/backward and strafe if the left joystick is BARELY moved (< 10% of full range). When this occurs, the robot moves, but it sounds like the gears are grinding in the swerved drive (doesn’t occur when rotating in place;!hence the physical gears are fine).

When the robot reboots and the driver station loses comms with it, one of the driver station errors is: “Warning 44000 Driver Station not keeping up with protocol rates”. There are also a host of other errors (socket disconnected, etc.) but those are probably due to the loss of comms.

I had originally thought that this might be a physical joystick or controller cable issue (ruled out), or a PIDF software loop issue. But has anyone else encountered this type of behavior, and if so, how did you fix it?

We are thankful for any assistance!!!

Check the logs on the driver station and maybe post them here. You are looking for something happening with the voltage at the time of the “crash”, or maybe messages. Also, see if you can do the things that cause problems with the robot up on blocks. If you can, it’s probably electrical or maybe the wheels aren’t aligned well. If you can’t maybe there’s something with software.
